    David Dinga year ago on Google
    1/5
    The hotel room was decent. However, the hotel restaurant is expensive without any of the benefits usually associated with expensive restaurants (good food, good service). In particular, it had one of the worst services I’ve ever …
    The hotel room was decent. However, the hotel restaurant is expensive without any of the benefits usually associated with expensive restaurants (good food, good service). In particular, it had one of the worst services I’ve ever experienced. There was only one waiter, and more than half the time, he wasn’t even in the restaurant. As a result, we had to wait a long time (30 minutes per wait?) to get the menu, then to order food, then to order again because half the items on the menu weren’t available (shouldn’t he have told us beforehand? In the end we just ordered a few random items on the menu because we were so exasperated being told everything we wanted was unavailable), then to get the food, and finally to pay. We were also the only people at the restaurant ordering food, so it’s not as if the waiter was overloaded. To rub salt into the wound, they decided to add a service charge to the bill — keep in mind that this is NOT the custom in Morocco nor in Tangier (tips are optional and are given for good service). Perhaps the long wait times were intentional, as by that time we were too tired to protest the charge. There are multiple restaurants nearby; eat anywhere except at this hotel.

    About this hotel

    A 2-minute walk from the beach, this casual hotel is also 2 km from Tanger Ville train station and 3 km from the Kasbah Museum. …

    The understated rooms provide flat-screen TVs, safe deposit boxes and minifridges. Suites feature sitting areas.

    Amenities consist of 4 restaurants (including a pizzeria), a serene piano bar and a nightclub. There's also an outdoor pool, as well as a spa. Parking and a breakfast buffet are available.
